Steps of the Analysis

  1. Data Loading

    • The dataset was imported and inspected using .info() and .head() to understand its structure.
    • It included various features related to British Airways flight bookings, such as booking class, trip type, purchase lead time, length of stay, total fare, and satisfaction scores.

  2. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

    • The data was analyzed using statistical summaries (.describe()) and visualized through charts to identify correlations, outliers, and missing values.
    • Functions like .duplicated() and .isnull().sum() were applied to check for data quality issues.
    • A seaborn heatmap was used to visualize feature correlations and understand relationships among variables.

  3. Data Preprocessing

    • Categorical variables (like trip type and class) were transformed into numerical values using OrdinalEncoder to prepare for model training.
    • The dataset was split into train and test sets using train_test_split().
    • Data normalization was applied using MinMaxScaler to scale numerical features between 0 and 1 for better model performance.
    • The dataset was also balanced using SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) to avoid bias toward the majority class.

  4. Model Training

    • Three machine learning models were tested:

      • Gradient Boosting Classifier
      • KNeighbors Classifier
      • Random Forest Classifier

    • Each model was trained to predict customer satisfaction or booking outcomes based on flight and customer attributes.

  5. Model Evaluation

    • Model performance was evaluated using metrics like:

      • Confusion Matrix
      • Classification Report (Precision, Recall, F1-score, Accuracy)

    • The Random Forest Classifier achieved the best performance overall, offering strong accuracy and balanced precision/recall.

    • SMOTE improved model fairness by allowing better recognition of underrepresented classes.

  6. Feature Analysis

    • A correlation analysis identified which variables had the strongest relationship with the target variable (likely satisfaction or booking class).
    • Feature selection could be further optimized by focusing on those with higher predictive importance.

Conclusion

The BA_Booking_ML project demonstrates a full data science workflow for predicting customer behavior in flight bookings. Efficiently applied EDA, feature encoding, data balancing, and scaling, followed by testing multiple classification models. The Random Forest Classifier achieved the most reliable results, successfully identifying patterns in the booking dataset.

In summary: This project highlights your ability to build a predictive model from raw airline data to actionable insights, covering all major machine learning steps from data cleaning to model evaluation. Future improvements could include:

  • Hyperparameter tuning (using RandomizedSearchCV or GridSearchCV)
  • Reducing less important variables to improve speed and interpretability
  • Adding more data to enhance generalization

import pandas as pd

1 Data Collect

To provide more context, below is a more detailed data description, explaining exactly what each column means:

  • num_passengers = number of passengers travelling
  • sales_channel = sales channel booking was made on
  • trip_type = trip Type (Round Trip, One Way, Circle Trip)
  • purchase_lead = number of days between travel date and booking date
  • length_of_stay = number of days spent at destination
  • flight_hour = hour of flight departure
  • flight_day = day of week of flight departure
  • route = origin -> destination flight route
  • booking_origin = country from where booking was made
  • wants_extra_baggage = if the customer wanted extra baggage in the booking
  • wants_preferred_seat = if the customer wanted a preferred seat in the booking
  • wants_in_flight_meals = if the customer wanted in-flight meals in the booking
  • flight_duration = total duration of flight (in hours)
  • booking_complete = flag indicating if the customer completed the booking

          "KNN": KNeighborsClassifier(),
          "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier(),

In[29]:
def fit_and_score(models, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    # Set random seed
    np.random.seed(42)
    # Make a dictionary to keep model scores
    model_scores = {}
    # Loop through models
    for name, model in models.items():
        # Fit the model to the data
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        # Evaluate the model and append its score to model_scores
        model_scores[name] = model.score(X_test, y_test)
    return model_scores
